Background

This bookdown aims to summarize and document the analysis performed and findings obtained as part of the Excellence in Agronomy (EiA) Initiative in Latin America and the Caribbean (LAC) region, specifically Peru. EiA is one of a series of CGIAR Initiatives that belongs to the Environmental health & biodiversity impact area and whose aim is to achieve sustainable intensification of smallholder farming systems, benefiting the agricultural resource base and its native organisms. Regarding the EiA LAC-Peru Use Case, the study area is located in the Chugay District, Sanchez Carrin Province, La Libertad region, and it is led by David A. Ramrez from CIP working hand in hand with local partners led by Ronal Otiniano from NGO Asociacin Pataz.

The main activities planned for the LAC-Peru Use Case were/are:

  1. Agronomic data digitization using the e-Agrology platform (in progress).
  2. Long-term demonstration trials of agronomic practices with potential for Climate Change mitigation (in progress).
  3. Remote sensing techniques applied to the LAC-Peru Use Case (in progress).
  4. Yield gap decomposition analysis (in progress).

For any request about the dataset or output/product generated and any comment about this bookdown, please contact DA Ramrez (d.ramirez@cgiar.org).

1 Agronomic data digitization

xx

1.1 e-Agrology platform

The e-Agrology platform (https://e-agrology.org/) is being used to collect general/relevant data about farmers, sowing events, used crops/varieties, technical visits to farmers plots, harvest events, and productivity (each of these is a log module of the e-Agrology). This platform has been developed by the CIMMYT team and it basically consists of well-thinking designed by experts surveys to obtain information directly from farmers. We plan to complete the records of the six previously mentioned modules (farmer, sowing, crop, visit, harvest, and productivity) for about 600 farmers. Currently, most modules are almost 100% done, with just the harvest and productivity modules being just at ~60% done. Since information related to inputs used by farmers (use of manure, fertilizers, etc.) is necessary for the stochastic frontiers analysis (see below), we plan to start recording data also in the inputs module of the e-Agrology.

Figure: Login window of the e-Agrology platform.

1.3 Data cleaning up

# clean R environment
# rm(list = ls())

# loading libraries
library(openxlsx)
library(dplyr)
library(stringr)
library(stringi)

# function to correct column names 
correct_colnames <- function(x, omit.str, r.this = "[.]", w.this = "_"){
  x = tolower(x)
  x = stri_trans_general(x, id="Latin-ASCII")  # stringi package
  x = str_replace(x, omit.str, "")             # stringr package
  x = str_replace_all(x, r.this, w.this)       # stringr package
  return(x)
}

# function to check which data frame a variable belongs to
check_colnames_df <- function(df1, df2, both){
  cnames = unique(c(df1, df2))
  df = data.frame(cnames, in.df1 = FALSE, in.df2 = FALSE, in.both = FALSE)
  for(i in 1:nrow(df)){
    df$in.df1[i] = df$cnames[i] %in% df1
    df$in.df2[i] = df$cnames[i] %in% df2
    df$in.both[i] = ifelse(isTRUE(df$in.df1[i]) & isTRUE(df$in.df2[i]), TRUE, FALSE)
  }
  return(df)
}

# variable to save each agronomic log

# after run 5: adding missing variables to p2

4 GrADS Analysis Script Example

This is a short example of a GrADS script written in GCL for analyzing and visualizing temperature data.

4.1 Prerequisites

  • GrADS software installed
  • Data file datafile.nc with 2-meter temperature variable available

4.2 How to Use

  1. Make sure you have GrADS installed on your system.
  2. Place the provided data file datafile.nc in the same directory as this script.
  3. Open a terminal or command prompt and navigate to the script directory.
  4. Run the script using the following command:
'open datafile.nc'
'set lon 0 360'
'set lat -90 90'
'd set time 1'
'd t2m'
'draw t2m'
